Time Series Regression Model for Forecasting Mortgaged Sales

1. Introduction

In this assignment we were expected to build a time series regression model for forecasting the April 2021 value of mortgaged sales in Turkey. The related data sets to be used as regressors are collected from EVDS. I gathered 5 data sets that can be used in explaining mortgaged sales, which are USD exchange rate, mortgage interest rates, house price index, the probability of buying or constructing a house, the probability of buying a car and the financial status of the household. The collected data sets are in monthly levels and between 2013-01 and 2021-03. In this report you will find the analysis of the target variable, the steps of building the model, evaluation of the final model and the forecast value for April 2021.

2. Analysis

2.1 Target Variable

First of all, we need to visualize the target variable to see if there is any pattern. Below you can find the line plot and the histogram of monthly mortgaged sales in Turkey.

We canât observe any particular pattern from the line plot. There are many ups and downs, but they are not a sign of seasonality component or cyclic pattern. Between 2013 and the start of 2018,plot has a stationary mean. However, there is a sharp decrease is mid-2018 and an abnormal increase in the summer of 2020. During pandemic, in 2020, public banks applied a discount to mortgage loan interest rates which acted as an incentive for people to buy mortgage loans.

Depending on the histogram we can say that the mortgage sales are normally distributed, however there are some outliers. These outliers are the sharp increase in the summer of 2020 that we observed in the line plot.

2.2 Independent Variables

We must observe the related data sets to find the candidates that can be used as regressors for the time regression model. Below you can find the line plot of each data and the correlation of each variable with the mortgaged sales.

#mortgage=Mortgaged Sales
#interest=Mortgage Interest Rates
#usd=USD Exchange Rate
#price=House Price Index
#status=Financial Status Of the Household
#probhouse=Probability of Buying a House
#probcar=Probability of Buying a Car

As you can see, mortgaged sales data has only one significant correlation, which is with the mortgage interest rates and they are negatively correlated. Thatâs why mortgage interest rates can be chosen as a regressor for the model.

We can say that residuals are normally distributed. In the residuals plot there are abnormally large residuals, which model does not account for. This residuals are due to outliers. Thatâs why we need to include them into our model.

3.3 Outliers

First, we need to define the outliers and then add them to our model as a dummy variable.

## [1] 101504 130721  76019

The outliers are observed in the summer of 2020, as we observed in the line plot.

fit4 <- lm(mortgage~as.factor(outlier)+interest+trend,data=sales)
summary(fit4)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mortgage ~ as.factor(outlier) + interest + trend, 
##     data = sales)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -23763.5  -3833.1    -44.5   4010.3  26233.3 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                     Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)         63292.91    2778.99   22.77   <2e-16 ***
## as.factor(outlier)1 57918.08    5131.34   11.29   <2e-16 ***
## interest            -2416.76     229.27  -10.54   <2e-16 ***
## trend                  58.27      34.70    1.68   0.0963 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 7967 on 95 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.7917, Adjusted R-squared:  0.7851 
## F-statistic: 120.4 on 3 and 95 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 10
## 
## data:  Residuals
## LM test = 16.408, df = 10, p-value = 0.08853

Addition of the outliers, significantly improved the model; residual standard error decreased to 7967 and adjusted r-squared increased to %78.51. Also, Residuals have a better normal distribution. Since itâs a sufficient model, I will choose this as my final model. However, please remark that this is not a perfect model. As we can see from the autocorrelation plot, lag 1 has a high value and still residuals do not perfectly follow the zero mean and constant variance assumption.
